Exploring the Forest Cover Data

Kevin

Thursday, April 02, 2015

We are working on the forest cover kaggle competition. Our GitHub repo contains the testing data which we have split up into a testing set and a training set.

In this challenge, you are given some information about a location and asked to predict which of 7 species of tree is the predominant species. Here are some exploratory plots. Im using this as a chance to check out some htmlwidgets so be prepared for a lot of different styles of plots.

My basic setup code

options(show.signif.stars = F, 
        digits = 3)

Data

Loading the data. Interestingly, it present both wilderness and soil type in wide format. Ive had to modify this for most of the plots. This part of the code is not very interesting.

# packages for data manipulation
library(tidyr)   ## to turn data to long format
library(dplyr)   ## for basic data manipulation

# grab right n characters of a string
substrRight <- function(x, n){
  substr(x, nchar(x)-n+1, nchar(x))
}

# data ------------------------------------------------

# load data
dat <- read.csv("data/our_train.csv", header = T, stringsAsFactors = F) %>% 
  tbl_df() %>% 
  select(-X)

# turn soil column into long format
soil_long <- dat %>% 
  gather(Soil, yn, -(Id:Wilderness_Area4), -Cover_Type) %>% 
  filter(yn == 1) %>% 
  mutate(
    Soil = as.character(Soil), 
    Soil = ifelse(nchar(Soil) == 10, substrRight(Soil, 1), substrRight(Soil, 2)), 
    Soil = as.numeric(Soil)
  ) %>% 
  select(-yn)

# turn wilderness to long format 
wild_long <- dat %>% 
  gather(Wilderness, yn, -(Id:Horizontal_Distance_To_Fire_Points), -(Soil_Type1:Soil_Type40), -Cover_Type) %>%
  filter(yn == 1) %>% 
  mutate(
    Wilderness = Wilderness %>% as.character %>% substrRight(1) %>% as.numeric) %>% 
  select(-yn)

# both wild and soil in long formation
all_long <- soil_long %>% 
  gather(Wilderness, yn, -(Id:Horizontal_Distance_To_Fire_Points), -Cover_Type, -Soil) %>% 
  filter(yn == 1) %>% 
  mutate(
    Wilderness = Wilderness %>% as.character %>% substrRight(1) %>% as.numeric) %>% 
  select(-yn)

Soil Type

One of the variable that is provided is the type of the soil. This is classified into one of 40 categories. I turned this into long format in a data.frame called soil_long in the preceding code chunk. Looking at the ggplot below, there are a couple of things I notice:

  1. Not all 40 soils are present (ex. soil 7, soil 15, etc)
  2. Some soils are a lot more common than others (looking at you soil 10)
  3. It looks like there are typically 3-4 tree species per soil type
# basic bar chart
library(ggplot2)
qplot(factor(Soil), data = soil_long, fill = factor(Cover_Type)) + 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "PuOr") + 
  theme_bw()

The streamgraph package provides really nice methods of visualizing how variables change over time. Its designed to work with time series so I had to hack it a bit to make this work.

# as a streamgraph
library(streamgraph)
soil_long %>% 
  group_by(Soil, Cover_Type) %>% 
  summarise(num = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(Soil = Soil %>% paste0(., "-01-01") %>% as.Date) %>%  ## super cheesy
  streamgraph("Cover_Type", "num", "Soil", interpolate="monotone") %>%
  sg_axis_x(1, "year", "%Y") %>%
  sg_legend(show=TRUE, label="Cover Type: ")%>%
  sg_fill_brewer("PuOr")

Some things jump out at me:

  1. Tree species (aka Cover Types) are actually represented fairly equally. Im not sure the streamgraph does a good job displaying this, but
library(rhandsontable)    
dat %>% 
  group_by(Cover_Type) %>% 
  summarise(n()) %>% 
  rhandsontable()  %>%
  hot_cols(columnSorting = TRUE)

  1. These variables are definitely related. I dont think Cover Type is ordered in any way.
  2. Im not sure I like streamgraphs from an exploratory setting. They do look really sleek so theyd probably be useful for presentations.

Wilderness Area

Wilderness Area is broken into four categories, but Im not exactly sure what any of the four categories represent. Heres a ggplot, but I actually like the dimple plot thats next a little bit better.

# basic bar chart
qplot(factor(Wilderness), data = wild_long, fill = factor(Cover_Type)) + 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "PuOr")

dimple is a JavaScript plotting library thats powered by d3. Kenton Russell put a ton of work into allowing R users to use dimple. He recently put together the rcdimple package and Im testing it here.

# using rcdimple
library(rcdimple)
wild_long %>% 
  group_by(Cover_Type, Wilderness) %>% 
  summarise(num = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  dimple(
    x = "Wilderness", 
    y = "num", 
    groups = "Cover_Type", 
    type = "bar", 
    data = .
  ) %>% 
  rcdimple::add_legend(x = 2, width = 300)  ## can get confused with ggvis package

I like this plot way better then the ggplot version, and I havent played with the parameters much.

  • It looks like green and purple (covers 3 and 6) go together
  • Orange (cover 4) only occurs in Wilderness 4. Interesting
  • Wilderness 2 is pretty rare
  • We should check with Terrill or some ecology guy who could tell us about this

Elevation by Wilderness

I use the rbokeh package to visualize elevation and wilderness vs cover. This package is an interface to the bokeh visualization library that is really nice.

Here, we really start to see some interesting patterns.

  1. First of all, elevation is really strongly related to wilderness type. 2500 meters appears to be an interesting cutoff. It is basically the boundary line for wilderness type 4. Almost all type 4 wilderness occurs below 2500 meters (about 98% of the time), and other wilderness types occur below 2500 meters only rarely. At 2500 meters, wilderness transitions to type 3. Types 1 and 2 typically occur above 2700 meters, though there are some cover type 5 trees in wilderness 1 at about 2500 meters.
wild_bokeh <- wild_long %>% 
  mutate(Wilderness = as.character(Wilderness), 
         Cover_Type = Cover_Type + runif(n(), -.1, .1))

library(rbokeh)
p <- figure() %>% 
  ly_points(Elevation, Cover_Type, data = wild_bokeh,
            glyph = Wilderness, color = Wilderness, alpha = 0.5, 
            hover = list(Elevation, Wilderness, Cover_Type))
p

As for predicting cover type, we almost certainly know that if its below 2500 meters it is type 3, 4, or 6. Cover type 7 clearly likes high elevation. Beyond that, Im not sure what information this provides.

Cover 1 vs 2

It sounds like our models are having trouble separating Cover 1 and 2. Lets try and find some differences.

In this plot, size is proportional to the number of points in each group. It appears that in wilderness 2, cover type 1 tends to have a much higher aspect. There are no species of cover type 1 in wilderness 4, but there are some cover type 2 there.

wild_long %>% 
  group_by(Cover_Type, Wilderness) %>% 
  summarise(Aspect = mean(Aspect), 
            num = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  dimple(y = "Aspect", 
         x = c("Wilderness", "Cover_Type"), 
         z = "num", 
         groups = "Cover_Type", 
         data = ., 
         type = "bubble") %>% 
  add_legend()

In wilderness 1 and 3, it looks as though Cover Type 1 might have slightly higher elevations.

wild_long %>% 
  group_by(Cover_Type, Wilderness) %>% 
  summarise(Elevation = mean(Elevation), 
            num = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  dimple(y = "Elevation", 
       x = c("Wilderness", "Cover_Type"), 
       z = "num", 
       groups = "Cover_Type", 
       data = ., 
       type = "bubble") %>% 
  add_legend() %>% 
  xAxis(type = "addCategoryAxis")
